An exploration of the geography of Toronto's built environment¶

Introduction¶

The purpose of this study is to use data to understand the geography of Toronto's built environment. The data used to achieve this is a socio-economic dataset at a neighbourhood resolution and an enhanced building dataset. Python was used in this study because it is widely adopted in geocomputation having bespoke spatial open-source packages.

Part 1¶

Variables and concepts¶

The selected variables were bedrooms_0 and bedrooms_1, the varying spatial distribution of these have powerful implications. The number of bedrooms inherently indicates the size, type and value of the associated property (Zietz et al., 2007). The selected variables were aggregated into one derived variable (bedrooms_less2).

Each neighbourhood geometry is different which is a consideration when comparing their associated attribute values. An equal number of properties may exist in 2 neighbourhoods, but one could have a larger area. This is described by the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) (Openshaw, 1984). Data munging was performed to mitigate this problem. The bedroom_ prefixed variables were aggregated into a Total for each neighbourhood, allowing bedrooms_less2 to be expressed as a percentage of the total. This approach helps achieve improved representation of the spatial distribution across areal units for easier direct comparison.

Spatial autocorrelation¶

The choropleth map in 1a was designed considering data has a positively skewed distribution. The data was split into 7 quantiles ensuring the same number of values in each bin. The sequential numerical attribute influenced the warm colour palette chosen and the colour-bar was quantized into those groups, influenced by Besancon et al. (2005).

1a shows that globally there is a pattern of clustering in the distribution of high percentage bedrooms_less2% neighbourhoods concentrated centrally towards the South (60%+). In order to further interpret the pattern in a statistical manner a spatial weights matrix was calculated using queen contiguity. This acts as a framework to calculate the spatial lag; the mean of the variable in the neighbourhood of the observation. The Moran plot in 1c shows, from the line of best fit, that there is positive spatial autocorrelation with a Morans I value of 0.54 (p<0.05). This means neighbourhoods with high bedrooms_less2% values are located near others with high bedrooms_less2% values.

1d isolates cluster locations in relation to their labelled quadrant in 1c, identifying local spatial autocorrelation. The coloured points in 1c (same colour as labels) are statistically significant (P<0.05). The result in 1d identifies a hot-spot to the south, cold-spots to the north-west and north-east suburbs and outliers to the West.

Part 2 - Regionalisation¶

Variables and concept¶

Considering MAUP it is known that aggregating the data with smaller units than neighbourhood level can help to display a different perspective on the urban geography of Toronto. In order to increase the resolution, a hex-grid polygon layer was used in place of neighbourhood geometry and the enhanced buildings dataset was aggregated using these polygons. The buildings dataset was enhanced to include a Type variable appended from an address_point dataset and the total_number of addresses for each building. The building data was further improved using raster data at 1m resolution (DTM/DSM) to generate a building_height at each building centroid. The building Types were made into dummy variables and recoded into 4 discrete groups: Tertiary, Hospitality, Residential and Other.

The buildings data for Toronto was grouped, using unsupervised machine learning algorithm K-means, into 9 categories describing the urban environment. All variables used for clustering are listed in the index column of Table 1. The partitions delineate regions of the city that were not captured using the neighbourhood geometry. Figure 2 shows the result of clustering.

2. Infer unjoined¶

In [ ]:
#define function for establishing nearest 'unmatched' points to building centroid, uses lambda function and KDTree for fast processing
#appends columns for those missing in join and distance value
def ckdnearest(gdA, gdB):
    nA = np.array(list(gdA.building_centroid.apply(lambda x: (x.x, x.y))))
    nB = np.array(list(gdB.geometry.apply(lambda x: (x.x, x.y))))
    btree = cKDTree(nB)
    dist, idx = btree.query(nA, k=1)
    gdf = pd.concat(
        [gdA.reset_index(drop=True), gdB.loc[idx, gdB.columns.isin(['GEO_ID','FCODE','FCODE_DES'])].reset_index(drop=True),
         pd.Series(dist, name='dist')], axis=1)
    return gdf

#use function described above
build_address_tc = ckdnearest(needed_buildings_address_tc2, needed_points_address_tc)
#add a distance of zero to those already joined
joined_buildings_address_tc['dist'] = 0
#
#drop index column to enable data to re-merge original table
build_address_tc = build_address_tc.drop(build_address_tc.columns[0],  axis=1)

#concatenate gdf for inferred and original join and set types to integer
full_building_table_tc = pd.concat([build_address_tc ,joined_buildings_address_tc])
full_building_table_tc = full_building_table_tc.astype({'FCODE': 'int', 'GEO_ID': 'int', 'fid': 'int'})

#delete obsolete variables
del needed_points_address_tc
del needed_buildings_address_tc2
del build_address_tc
del joined_buildings_address_tc

#Define function to dissolve hex-grids
def dissolve(gs):
    '''
    Take a series of polygons and dissolve them into a single one
    Arguments
    ---------
    gs        : GeoSeries
                Sequence of polygons to be dissolved
    Returns
    -------
    dissolved : Polygon
                Single polygon containing all the polygons in `gs`
    '''
    return gs.unary_union

# Dissolve the polygons based on 9cls
db_groups = gpd.GeoSeries(joined_hex.groupby(joined_hex['db9cls_final'])\
                                .apply(dissolve),
                             crs=joined_hex.crs
                            )
#make variable a gdf
db_groups = gpd.GeoDataFrame({"geometry": db_groups.geometry,
                                              "cluster": db_groups.index
                                             }, crs="EPSG:3979")

Observations¶

The regionalisation process illustrates, from a town planning perspective, that the built environment of Toronto is divided by a belt of lower density urbanisation that separates the CBD from the suburbs. Individual clusters support this observation (table 1). 0 has the tallest buildings, suggesting it is the CBD. 1 distinguishes regions where buildings are sparser and have a lower number of total addresses, suggesting parkland. 4 shows lower density Residential with lower values of other Types, suggesting suburbs. 8 has the highest number of total addresses and ratio of buildings to addresses, suggesting apartments and high-density living spaces.

Conclusion¶

Comparing the regionalisation to the choropleth map, the regions suggest the urban composition is more complex than administratively defined boundaries indicate. Prior uses of k-means clustering in a spatial context suggest these delineations have capacity to inform town planning (Zhi et al., 2016). Further applications of this regionalisation include predicting house prices, targeting areas for development, identifying regions lacking certain services, habitat delineation and police patrol districting (Wei et al., 2021).

#Calculate the raster data using mosaicing - Run on both DTM and DSM
# File and folder paths
dirpath = "C:\\GeographicDataScience\\ENVS563 - GEOGRAPHIC DATA SCIENCE\\Raster\\DTM"
out_fp = os.path.join(dirpath, "Toronto_DTMx1m_Mosaic.tif")

# Make a search criteria to select the DEM files
search_criteria = "DTM*.tif"
q = os.path.join(dirpath, search_criteria)
# glob function can be used to list files from a directory with specific criteria
dem_fps = glob.glob(q)

# List for the source files
src_files_to_mosaic = []

# Iterate over raster files and add them to source -list in 'read mode'
for fp in dem_fps:
    src = rasterio.open(fp)
    src_files_to_mosaic.append(src)

# Merge function returns a single mosaic array and the transformation info
mosaic, out_trans = merge(src_files_to_mosaic)

# Plot the result
show(mosaic, cmap='terrain')

out_meta = src.meta.copy()

# Update the metadata
out_meta.update({"driver": "GTiff",
                 "height": mosaic.shape[1],
                 "width": mosaic.shape[2],
                 "transform": out_trans,
                 "crs": "+proj=utm +zone=17 +ellps=GRS80 +units=m +no_defs "
                 }
                )
